<div id="review_1506573465" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1506573465" />
    <a title="Neil Hepworth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5547618-neil-hepworth"><img alt="Neil Hepworth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442971609p2/5547618.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1506573465?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neil Hepworth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neil Hepworth" href="/user/show/5547618-neil-hepworth">Neil Hepworth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6497182-get-shorty">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1506573465" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7955718870394039980">Can someone explain the appeal of this book to me? I&apos;m sure it&apos;s a great movie because there&apos;s only 90 minutes of material stretched over 300 pages. I mean, I guess if you like reading about how movies are made (kinda), then you might like some of the scenes, but man...I just don&apos;t get it. The actual plot, when it showed up, was pretty good - there were just so many scenes when nothin&apos; much happened. I dunno.<br/><br/>I read this book &apos;cause my wife and I are watching <i>Justified</i> and I thought this would be</span>
  <span id="freeText7955718870394039980" style="display:none">Can someone explain the appeal of this book to me? I'm sure it's a great movie because there's only 90 minutes of material stretched over 300 pages. I mean, I guess if you like reading about how movies are made (kinda), then you might like some of the scenes, but man...I just don't get it. The actual plot, when it showed up, was pretty good - there were just so many scenes when nothin' much happened. I dunno.<br /><br />I read this book 'cause my wife and I are watching <i>Justified</i> and I thought this would be a good one to read since it's Elmore Leonard's most popular. Hm. Bad idea. I'll read a few other books and then come back to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/85211.Pronto" title="Pronto by Elmore Leonard" rel="nofollow noopener">Pronto</a> or something that's a bit more in line with the action on the TV show. But if it doesn't do it for me after that, well...then I might have to move on to greener pastures. After all, all them Star Wars books on my bookshelf ain't gonna read themselves.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7955718870394039980" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


